===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|aleggen}}, borrowed from {{der|en|xno|aleger}}, the form from {{der|en|fro|esligier|t=to acquit}}, from {{der|en|ML.||*exlītigāre|to clear at law}}, from {{der|en|la|ex||out}} + {{m|la|lītigō||sue at law}}, the meaning from Old French {{m|fro|alleguer}}, from Latin {{m|la|allēgāre}}, present active infinitive of {{m|la|allēgō||send, depute; relate, mention, adduce}}, from {{m|la|ad||to}} + {{m|la|lēgō||send}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete|transitive}} To [[state]] under [[oath]], to [[plead]].
# {{lb|en|archaic}} To [[cite]] or [[quote]] an author or his work ''for'' or ''against''.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[adduce]] (something) as a reason, excuse, support etc.
#* {{RQ:Montaigne Florio Essayes|chapter=39|book=I|passage=I will further '''alleage''' a storie{{...}}to make us palpably feele his naturall condition.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To make a [[claim]] as [[justification]] or [[proof]]; to make an assertion without proof.
#: {{ux|en|The agency '''alleged''' that my credit history had problems.}}

